{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 03:29:25.946042", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report — SDN Spine–Leaf Fabric\\n\\nScope and expectation\\n- Topology: 1 spine (spine_1) and 2 leafs (leaf_1, leaf_2). Each leaf connects to two hosts in 10.0.0.0/24 and to the spine via point-to-point links. All switches join 20.0.0.0/24 and are controlled via OpenFlow by a controller at 20.0.0.100.\\n- Expected behavior: Intra-subnet L2 connectivity across and within leaves; ARP broadcast/flood should work; controller should program correct forwarding flows.\\n\\nHigh-level health assessment\\n- Overall state: Severely degraded. End-to-end connectivity is broken both within the same leaf and across leaves. ARP fails. Evidence indicates incorrect/malformed OpenFlow rules pushed by the SDN controller, including a blanket drop rule on leaf_2 and self-output/hairpin rules on spine_1 and misdirected outputs on leaf_1.\\n\\nEvidence and findings\\n1) End-to-end reachability\\n- Pings fail across and within leaves:\\n  - host_1_1 → host_1_2: 100% loss\\n  - host_1_1 → host_2_1: “Destination Host Unreachable” from 10.0.0.1; 100% loss\\n  - host_2_1 → host_2_2: “Destination Host Unreachable” from 10.0.0.9; 100% loss\\n- ARP state on hosts:\\n  - host_1_1: 10.0.0.2 shows STALE; 10.0.0.9 FAILED (indicates ARP resolution failure to remote leaf)\\n  - host_2_1: no ARP neighbors learned on eth0 (ARP resolution failing even intra-leaf)\\n\\n2) Switch/controller control-plane status\\n- All OVS bridges report Controller \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\" is_connected: true\\n- Switches can ping controller 20.0.0.100 with high RTT (~730–787 ms), but reachable.\\n- Note: systemctl reports openvswitch-switch “inactive (dead)” on switches, but OVS is operational (ovs-vsctl/ofctl work). Likely a service management artifact; not the primary issue.\\n\\n3) Data-plane OpenFlow state (key anomalies)\\n- leaf_2 (critical):\\n  - dump-flows: Single high-priority drop rule:\\n    - priority=100 actions=drop, packet count ~88,953\\n  - dump-ports: High RX counts on many ports; all TX counters are 0. This is consistent with a blanket drop (no forwarding out).\\n  - Impact: All traffic (including ARP broadcasts) is dropped on leaf_2. Hosts host_2_1 and host_2_2 cannot even communicate with each other on the same leaf.\\n\\n- leaf_1 (misprogrammed forwarding):\\n  - Observed per-flow entries match specific MAC pairs but send to incorrect egress ports:\\n    - Example: in_port=1 (eth0, host_1_1), dl_dst=host_1_2’s MAC → actions=output:11\\n    - Expected: output should be port 2 (eth1) for host_1_2 (per topology leaf_1:eth0↔host_1_1, leaf_1:eth1↔host_1_2)\\n  - Similar anomalies exist for other MAC pairs (local flows forwarded to uplinks like ports 10/11/12 rather than local access ports).\\n  - Likely missing/broken broadcast/flood rules for ARP (no evidence of dl_dst=ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff flood entries).\\n  - dump-ports: Significant TX on many ports, but not resulting in working connectivity, consistent with misdirected egress.\\n\\n- spine_1 (invalid/hairpin behavior):\\n  - Sample flows indicate self-output/hairpin actions, e.g., in_port=X → actions=output:X for specific MAC pairs.\\n  - Outputting back to the ingress port is functionally equivalent to discard (OVS typically does not send packets out the same ingress), which prevents transit forwarding across the fabric.\\n\\n4) Topology/ports consistency cross-check\\n- OVS port mappings:\\n  - leaf_1: port 1(eth0) and 2(eth1) are host-facing per provided topology. Flows directing host_1_1→host_1_2 traffic to port 11/12 instead of port 2 demonstrate incorrect port selection by the controller.\\n- Link state:\\n  - OVS-ofctl show for all switches indicates all data ports LIVE. No obvious physical link down event.\\n\\nLocalized fault domains\\n- leaf_2: Entire leaf is effectively a blackhole due to a high-priority drop rule in table 0. This directly explains failures for host_2_1 ↔ host_2_2 (same leaf).\\n- leaf_1: Local L2 forwarding is misprogrammed (local traffic forwarded to uplinks instead of access port), and broadcast handling appears absent/incorrect.\\n- spine_1: Transit forwarding rules loop packets back to ingress (hairpin), so inter-leaf forwarding cannot work.\\n\\nRoot cause hypothesis\\n- Controller-side misconfiguration/bug in the OpenFlow application/pipeline:\\n  - Installed a default high-priority drop on leaf_2, blocking all traffic.\\n  - Programmed incorrect egress ports for MAC pairs on leaf_1 (host-local flows pointing to uplinks).\\n  - Programmed spine_1 with self-output rules, preventing transit forwarding.\\n- Not a physical/link failure: All interfaces report LIVE, switches are connected to the controller, and there’s no evidence of local interface errors.\\n\\nImpact\\n- Complete loss of L2 connectivity across the 10.0.0.0/24 subnet:\\n  - Intra-leaf (leaf_2) traffic is dropped.\\n  - Intra-leaf (leaf_1) traffic is misrouted and fails.\\n  - Inter-leaf traffic cannot transit via spine_1 due to hairpin rules and drop on leaf_2.\\n- ARP broadcast and learning are impaired network-wide.\\n\\nKey artifacts (for reference)\\n- leaf_2 dump-flows: only “priority=100 actions=drop” with high packet counters.\\n- leaf_2 dump-ports: RX nonzero, TX zero on all ports.\\n- leaf_1 dump-flows: host_1_1 ↔ host_1_2 traffic sent to port 11/12 (uplink/incorrect) instead of port 2.\\n- spine_1 dump-flows: actions=output:<same ingress port>.\\n- Host ARP behavior: host_2_1 cannot resolve ARP even within same leaf; host_1_1 shows stale ARP for host_1_2 implying ARP/flooding issues.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- The fabric is experiencing a controller-induced forwarding outage. The SDN controller at 20.0.0.100 is connected but is pushing incorrect OpenFlow rules:\\n  - A blanket drop on leaf_2,\\n  - Misprogrammed local forwarding on leaf_1,\\n  - Hairpin/self-output rules on spine_1.\\n- This collectively breaks ARP and all L2 forwarding, resulting in total loss of host-to-host connectivity., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='dd1de04e-c7f2-477b-814d-01b29f54ef22'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
